In the programming language Rust, trait objects are a way to create objects that implement a trait, which is a set of behaviors that the object must implement. Trait objects are created by calling a function that returns a reference to the trait object, and then using that reference to call the methods of the trait on the object.

Traits are a way to define a set of behaviors that a type should implement, but it is not a concrete type. Trait objects are a way to create an instance of a trait, which is a concrete object that can be used like any other object in the program.

